quran[14]{c,v,t}:
  13,5,"ňĻNow,ňļ if anything should amaze you ňĻO Prophetňļ, then it is their question: ‚ÄúWhen we are reduced to dust, will we really be raised as a new creation?‚ÄĚ It is they who have disbelieved in their Lord. It is they who will have shackles around their necks. And it is they who will be the residents of the Fire. They will be there forever"
  13,6,"They ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ to hasten the torment rather than grace, though there have ňĻalreadyňļ been ňĻmanyňļ torments before them. Surely your Lord is full of forgiveness for people, despite their wrongdoing, and your Lord is truly severe in punishment"
  13,7,"The disbelievers say, ‚ÄúIf only a sign could be sent down to him from his Lord.‚ÄĚ You ňĻO Prophetňļ are only a warner. And every people had a guide"
  13,8,God knows what every female bears and what increases and decreases in the wombs.¬†And with Him everything is determined with precision
  13,9,"ňĻHe is theňļ Knower of the seen and the unseen‚ÄĒthe All-Great, Most Exalted"
  13,10,"It is the same ňĻto Himňļ whether any of you speaks secretly or openly, whether one hides in the darkness of night or goes about in broad daylight"
  13,11,"For each one there are successive angels before and behind, protecting them by God‚Äôs command. Indeed, God would never change a people‚Äôs state ňĻof favourňļ until they change their own state ňĻof faithňļ. And if it is God‚Äôs Will to torment a people, it can never be averted, nor can they find a protector other than Him"
  13,12,"He is the One Who shows you lightning, inspiring ňĻyou withňļ hope and fear,¬†and produces heavy clouds"
  13,13,"The thunder glorifies His praises, as do the angels in awe of Him. He sends thunderbolts, striking with them whoever He wills. Yet they dispute about God. And He is tremendous in might"
  13,14,"Calling upon Him ňĻaloneňļ is the truth. But those ňĻidolsňļ the pagans invoke besides Him ňĻcanňļ never respond to them in any way. ňĻIt isňļ just like someone who stretches out their hands to water, ňĻasking itňļ to reach their mouths, but it can never do so. The calls of the disbelievers are only in vain"
  13,15,"To God ňĻaloneňļ bow down ňĻin submissionňļ¬†all those in the heavens and the earth‚ÄĒwillingly or unwillingly‚ÄĒas do their shadows, morning and evening"
  13,16,"Ask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúWho is the Lord of the heavens and the earth?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúGod!‚ÄĚ Ask ňĻthemňļ, ‚ÄúWhy ňĻthenňļ have you taken besides Him lords who cannot even benefit or protect themselves?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúCan the blind and the sighted be equal? Or can darkness and light be equal?‚ÄĚ¬†Or have they associated with God partners who ňĻsupposedlyňļ produced a creation like His, leaving them confused between the two creations? Say, ‚ÄúGod is the Creator of all things, and He is the One, the Supreme.‚ÄĚ"
  13,17,"He sends down rain from the sky, causing the valleys to flow, each according to its capacity. The currents then carry along rising foam, similar to the slag produced from metal that people melt in the fire for ornaments or tools. This is how God compares truth to falsehood. The ňĻworthlessňļ residue is then cast away, but what benefits people remains on the earth. This is how God sets forth parables"
  13,18,"Those who respond to ňĻthe call ofňļ their Lord will have the finest reward. As for those who do not respond to Him, even if they were to possess everything in the world twice over, they would certainly offer it to ransom themselves. They will face strict judgment, and Hell will be their home. What an evil place to rest"